Belfast Telegraph There's something about sound of birdsong on an April morning that can lift the spirit, making the soul soar. We may never know exactly what it is about their melodies that delights the human ear, but research proves beyond doubt that sounds of nature have a profoundly beneficial effect on our mental and physical well being. Professor Robert Paine and his Cambridge University team conducted a challenge to test laughter against the sound of birdsong. A group of volunteers were guaranteed 30 minutes of hysteria every day for two months. Half were placed in a room redecorated to resemble an old fashioned doctor's surgery. The other half were placed in a room awash with chirping birdsong, also for two months. Even though their daily dose of laughter was for twice the Price of birdsong, all the participants said they preferred laughing up a storm.
